THE FOUR LEVELS OF PROTEIN STRUCTURE: Meeting the Hormone Insulin
p. 1 of 7

BACKGROUND: 

Proteins provide the machinery and much of the structure of our cells.  In this activity you will explore one small messenger protein made by the pancreas, the hormone insulin, and the four levels of protein structure required for it to take its shape. Those levels of structure are typical of most proteins.
		
Insulin is secreted into the bloodstream after a meal in response to the intake of glucose (sugar) or the production of it from other food molecules.  Cells in many parts of our body have insulin receptors on their surface. When insulin molecules attach to these receptors, other molecules are switched on in a chain reaction that allows glucose in the blood to enter a cell. 

The chart below shows both normal glucose and insulin levels in a person over 24 hours. Without Insulin, you could eat lots of food and still be in the state of starvation, since many of your cells could not access the calories you need. Most often people associate insulin with the disease diabetes.  For those with diabetes, the pancreas lacks the ability to produce or release the right amount of insulin.  They must take insulin daily.

  
http://www.lantus.com/information/management/insulin.html

In this activity we will begin to look at the structure of insulin in order to analyze, first, what is involved in each level of protein structure and, next, how the structure helps insulin perform its very specialized function in our bodies.

   

